  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad and global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity and is prohibited by laws in virtually every country. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as from drug trafficking, corruption, or fraud) appear legitimate by disguising the true origin of the funds.\n\nInternational bodies, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, have established global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Most countries have enacted legislation and established regulatory frameworks to criminalize money laundering and require financial institutions to implement measures to detect and report suspicious transactions.\n\nFor example:\n- In the **United States**, money laundering is illegal under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act**.\n- In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** provide a legal framework for member states to combat money laundering.\n- In **China**, money laundering is criminalized under the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** and the **Criminal Law**.\n\nOverall, money laundering is universally condemned because it undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates criminal activities, and harms economies. Efforts to combat it are a priority for governments, international organizations, and financial institutions worldwide.",
